Transit Gateway.

When the number of V-P-Cs that need to talk grows past a handful, peering's full mesh stops being sustainable. Transit Gateway, or T-G-W, replaces the mesh with a hub-and-spoke topology. Every V-P-C attaches once to the Transit Gateway, and the Transit Gateway routes between them. Ten V-P-Cs that would have needed forty-five peering connections need just ten attachments instead.

The Transit Gateway is regional, but it supports rich attachment types: V-P-Cs, Site-to-Site V-P-N connections, Direct Connect Gateways, and even other Transit Gateways for inter-region peering. Routing is transitive by default, meaning any attachment can reach any other, which immediately raises the question of how you keep environments separated.

The answer is T-G-W route tables. A Transit Gateway has multiple route tables, and each attachment is associated with one of them. A dev attachment associated with the dev route table sees other dev V-P-Cs but not prod; the prod route table sees prod V-P-Cs and the on-prem attachment but not dev. That's how you build a single global network with enforced segmentation, and it's the reason Transit Gateway is the backbone of almost every multi-V-P-C and hybrid design at scale.
